title: Design and Implementation of a Piano Learning System using a Real-Time Fingering Recognition
title_en: Design and Implementation of a Piano Learning System using a Real-Time Fingering Recognition
abstract: 本研究はリアルタイム運指認識を用いてピアノ学習を支援するシステムの設計と実装を扱っている。本研究はカメラ映像から演奏中の指の動きを検出してPC上で処理し，鍵盤投影装置とディスプレイを通じて即時の視覚フィードバックを行う構成を提案している。
abstract_en: This work addresses the design and implementation of a piano learning support system using real-time fingering recognition. This work detects finger motion from camera images, processes the data on a PC, and provides immediate visual feedback via keyboard projection and display.
positioning_summary: 本研究はリアルタイム運指認識をピアノ学習支援に適用する研究領域に位置づけられている。本文献は演奏者の運指を自動的に認識して即時に視覚提示することによってピアノ学習者の演奏支援というギャップを埋めることを目指している。
positioning_summary_en: This study is positioned in the research area of applying real-time fingering recognition to piano learning support. This study aims to fill the gap in piano learner support by automatically recognizing fingerings and presenting them visually in real time.
purpose_summary: 本研究の目的は鍵盤上の運指をリアルタイムで認識して学習者に即時の視覚フィードバックを提供するピアノ学習システムを設計・実装することである。本文献はピアノ学習者を対象に演奏中の運指を自動認識して視覚的に提示することで学習効率を向上させることを目的としている。
purpose_summary_en: The purpose of this work is to design and implement a piano learning system that recognizes fingering on the keyboard in real time and provides immediate visual feedback to learners. This work targets piano learners by automatically recognizing fingerings during performance and presenting them visually to improve learning efficiency.
method_summary: 本研究はカメラ映像の運指認識モジュールとMIDI鍵盤からの情報を受けてPC上で映像生成を行い，鍵盤投影用プロジェクタとディスプレイへ出力するハードウェアとソフトウェアの統合を実装している。本文献はPC（CPU相当2.60GHz，約2.5GB RAM），カメラ（640×480，30fps相当），画像処理ライブラリを用いたリアルタイム画像処理とプロジェクタやスクリーン，プラスチック板を組み合わせた出力構成を具体的に示している。
method_summary_en: This work implements integration of a fingering recognition module from camera images with MIDI keyboard input, generating visuals on a PC and outputting to a keyboard projector and display. This work uses a PC (approximately 2.60GHz CPU and 2.5GB RAM), a camera (640×480 at about 30 fps), image processing libraries, and a setup combining projector, screen, and plastic board for real-time processing.
evaluation_summary: 本研究は指定したクラシック曲を用いた実験評価を行い，演奏データに対する運指認識の評価を実施した。本文献は実験で複数の演奏検証を行い平均値や分散を含む定量的な性能指標（例: 2.3（1.9）や0.5（1.0））や5%に関連する数値を報告している。
evaluation_summary_en: This work conducted experimental evaluation using specified classical pieces and evaluated fingering recognition on collected performance data. This work reports multiple performance verifications and quantitative metrics including mean and variance values (e.g., 2.3 (1.9), 0.5 (1.0)) and figures related to 5%.

Authors: Yoshinari Takegawa, Tsutomu Terada, Masahiko Tsukamoto

Abstract: This work addresses the design and implementation of a piano learning support system using real-time fingering recognition. This work detects finger motion from camera images, processes the data on a PC, and provides immediate visual feedback via keyboard projection and display.
Positioning Summary: This study is positioned in the research area of applying real-time fingering recognition to piano learning support. This study aims to fill the gap in piano learner support by automatically recognizing fingerings and presenting them visually in real time.
Purpose Summary: The purpose of this work is to design and implement a piano learning system that recognizes fingering on the keyboard in real time and provides immediate visual feedback to learners. This work targets piano learners by automatically recognizing fingerings during performance and presenting them visually to improve learning efficiency.
Method Summary: This work implements integration of a fingering recognition module from camera images with MIDI keyboard input, generating visuals on a PC and outputting to a keyboard projector and display. This work uses a PC (approximately 2.60GHz CPU and 2.5GB RAM), a camera (640×480 at about 30 fps), image processing libraries, and a setup combining projector, screen, and plastic board for real-time processing.
Evaluation Summary: This work conducted experimental evaluation using specified classical pieces and evaluated fingering recognition on collected performance data. This work reports multiple performance verifications and quantitative metrics including mean and variance values (e.g., 2.3 (1.9), 0.5 (1.0)) and figures related to 5%.
